"However, we do not see any US-compliant response," he said.
"Without confidence in the USA there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm unilaterally at first."
Although Ri has re-used the complaints concerning Washington's resistance to a "phased" denuclearization with which North Korea would be awarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement has been important because it has not completely refused unilateral denuclearization as it has already done in the past by Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a U.S. President and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim committed to working towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea sought a formal end-of-war agreement in the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States stated that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposed appeals to ease the rigid international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The USA insists on the need to "have first denuclearisation" and to increase the pressure level with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive way and even oppose the "declaration of the end of war", said Ri.
"The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is an illusion of those who don't know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust."
Ri did not refer to programmes of a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced to the UN at the beginning of the week.
On the other hand, the minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the counterpart of this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the USA, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from last year's speech at the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target the US territory with the North Korean missiles after "the president of evil" Trump had called Kim a "missile man" engaged in a suicide mission.
Before the United Nations Trump, which last year had threatened to "destruct completely" North Korea, he praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the disarmament path, but declared that much still needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in force until the denuclearization of North Korea.
Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a deadline, stating that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
