Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has driven all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counteract the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fed by caffeine.
A university student found that students at the university number one in the world often have no idea of the basic concepts of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed the course, which he considers to be the first of this type in the USA.
He had the idea of starting the course after a conference that had given about the impact of sleeplessness on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said to me, 'Why is this only told to me now, when I'm last year?'
He said that no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me very much," he told The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to the students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits can help academic and athletic performance and improve general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director general of health services at the university, said that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were suffering from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course provides for a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select cups of coffee, curtains, gymnastic shoes and books to know the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performances are influenced by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not change the behavior of students immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as you have the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the "black night to study" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to a lack of sleep to a growing problem.
Sleeping enough and with a good quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, marriage, anxiety, explained and even should be used to avoid fattening because lack of sleep brings the brain into an unprecedented way, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the Faculty of Chemical and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after having followed one of his lessons last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduates to follow a similar curriculum before joining this competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler advised students to set a wake-up for when to go to bed, as well as for when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can turn the circadian rhythm into tilt, leading to sleeping problems.
