Syria says it is ready for the return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the devastated country for over seven years of war.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, Minister for Foreign Affairs Walid al-Moualem said that the conditions of the country are improving.
"Today the situation on the territory is more stable and secure thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to recover the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
Now there are all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that have had to leave because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures that have affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
According to the United Nations estimate, more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
Another six million who still live in Syria need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian regime would gladly accept assistance to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept any aid subject to conditions or by those countries which supported the insurrection.
